          "body": "The chapter's eschatological turn begins at verse 6 with a scene that would have been culturally explosive for Isaiah's audience. 'The Lord of hosts will prepare a lavish banquet for all peoples on this mountain' — not for Israel only, but for all peoples, all nations. The banquet's extravagance is described with repeated emphasis: aged wine, choice marrow, refined and aged wine. In the ancient Near East, lavish feasting was the image of covenant peace, royal abundance, and shalom fully realized. Isaiah places this universal feast on Zion — the mountain that was Israel's exclusive center — and opens the guest list to all nations. Simultaneously, on that same mountain, the Lord 'will swallow up the covering which is over all peoples, even the veil which is stretched over all nations' (25:7). The veil (*massekhah*) is the shroud of death, ignorance, and separation from God that has hung over the Gentile world. The double image — feasting and unveiling — forms a single eschatological act: inclusion and illumination together. Paul's use of analogous veil imagery in 2 Corinthians 3:14-16 suggests the veil's removal is accomplished through the preaching of the gospel."
