          "title": "The conquest of death and the wiping of tears (25:8-9)",
          "body": "Verse 8 is the chapter's theological summit and one of the most freighted sentences in the entire Old Testament: 'He will swallow up death for all time.' The verb *bala* (to swallow up) was used in verse 7 of the veil's removal; now God turns the same consuming power against death itself. Death is not merely postponed, not mitigated, not explained — it is *swallowed* forever (*netsach*). This is the earliest explicit Old Testament promise of death's total, permanent abolition. Paul quotes it directly in 1 Corinthians 15:54 as the text fulfilled at the bodily resurrection of the dead. The second and third promises of verse 8 are equally concrete: 'the Lord God will wipe tears away from all faces' — an act of personal, individual tenderness applied universally — and 'He will remove the reproach of His people from all the earth.' Shame, grief, and mortality are the three dimensions of the curse that verse 8 explicitly reverses. The congregational response in verse 9 shows what happens when this day arrives: the waiting community recognizes its God ('Behold, this is our God'), names the waiting that preceded the moment ('for whom we have waited'), and breaks into rejoicing proportional to the duration of the hope deferred. Twice they say 'we have waited' — the repetition is not rhetorical redundancy but the accumulated weight of years of expectant endurance now suddenly released."
