        "title": "Praise grounded in historical judgment — wonders, plans, and faithfulness",
        "range": "25:1-3",
        "excerpt": "O Lord, You are my God; I will exalt You, I will give thanks to Your name; for You have worked wonders, plans formed long ago, with perfect faithfulness.",
        "body": "Isaiah 25 opens in the first-person singular — not collective Israel, but the prophet himself in personal address: 'You are *my* God.' This is not the impersonal theology of the nations-oracles that precede it (chs. 13-23). It is intimate doxology arising from the same man who has been proclaiming judgment for eleven chapters. The worship is intelligently grounded: Isaiah praises God 'for' a specific act — the demolition of the fortified city of verse 2. Praise in Isaiah 25 is not emotionally generated; it is inference from observed divine conduct.\n\nThe theological weight of verse 1 rests on two phrases: 'plans formed long ago' (*etsah merachoq*, counsel from afar) and 'with perfect faithfulness' (*emunah omen*, faithfulness of faithfulness — a double superlative). Together they say that the destroyed city is not a surprise reversal but the execution of an eternal, pre-formed plan carried out with flawless reliability. This is Isaiah's response to the question every generation asks when empires fall: was God in control of this? His answer is yes — and He planned it before the empire was founded.\n\nThe consequence stated in verse 3 is missiological. A 'strong people' will glorify God, and 'cities of ruthless nations will revere' Him — not because they repented voluntarily, but because they witnessed an act of divine judgment that surpassed all human explanation. The demolition of the unnamed city produces reverence in nations that would not otherwise have offered it. This is one of Isaiah's recurring themes: God's judgment on anti-God power is simultaneously an act of witness to the nations (cf. Isaiah 37:20, where Hezekiah prays that Assyria's defeat would prove to all kingdoms that the Lord alone is God).\n\nThe identity of the 'city' in verse 2 has generated centuries of commentary. The leading candidates are Babylon (favored by the LXX, Origen, and Childs), an anonymous Assyrian city, or an eschatological 'city of chaos' (*qiryah tohu*, Isaiah 24:10 — directly preceding this passage). The deliberate anonymity is almost certainly intentional: the city is a type, not a single historical referent. Every regime that fortifies itself against the Lord qualifies. Calvin's comment stands: 'By *city* he designates whatever men build to resist God.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pele* (wonders, v.1) is the word for extraordinary, transcendent acts — the same root used for the names of the messianic child in Isaiah 9:6 (*Wonderful Counselor*). *Etsah merachoq* — counsel from far away, from antiquity — emphasizes the pre-temporal origin of the divine plan. *Emunah omen* — faithfulness of faithfulness — is a doubled noun construction functioning as superlative."
